      "Nicotine is what makes tobacco addictive, so when you quit smoking your body has to get used to not having nicotine. This lack of nicotine is what causes nicotine withdrawal symptoms. Nicotine withdrawal is challenging for most smokers, but the good news is that the worst withdrawal symptoms usually last less than two weeks, even though that stretch of time can be really tough.",
      "Most people experience cravings for cigarettes after they quit, and these thoughts and feelings can range from mild to intense or even overwhelming. Helpful ways to manage cravings include making a quit plan ahead of time, distracting yourself when an urge hits, and identifying your personal triggers so you can avoid or prepare for them. You can also text CRAVE to 47848 for support, talk to a healthcare provider about quit-smoking medications, and use a tracking app to stay on course.",
