      "The FDA has alerted the public to thousands of reports of serious lung illnesses associated with vaping, including dozens of deaths. Many of the suspect products tested were THC-containing vaping products, though some contained nicotine mixtures or nicotine alone. The CDC identified Vitamin E acetate as a chemical of concern in these lung injuries and recommends avoiding products that contain it, THC-containing vaping products (especially from informal sources), and any modified or street-purchased products.",
      "E-cigarettes are not FDA-approved as a quit-smoking aid, and there is no conclusive scientific evidence that vaping is effective for long-term smoking cessation. In a study of more than 800 people who vaped to quit smoking, only about nine percent reported they had stopped smoking after one year. European research found that adult smokers who vaped nicotine were less likely to have quit and tended to smoke more cigarettes overall. Seven FDA-approved quit aids exist that are proven safe and effective when used as directed.",
