      "Different withdrawal symptoms follow different timelines. Anger, frustration, and irritability tend to peak within 1 week of quitting and may last 2 to 4 weeks. Anxiety usually builds over the first 3 days after quitting and may last several weeks. Depression usually begins within the first day, continues for a couple of weeks, and goes away within a month.",
      "People who use tobacco get used to having a certain level of nicotine in their body, so after quitting, cravings develop when the body wants nicotine. Cravings can begin within an hour or two after the last use of tobacco and may occur frequently for the next few days or weeks before getting farther apart as time passes. During a craving, mood may change and heart rate and blood pressure may go up.",
      "To cope with cravings, remind yourself that cravings will pass, and avoid situations and activities you used to associate with using tobacco. As a substitute for smoking, try chewing on carrots, pickles, apples, celery, sugarless gum, or hard candy, since keeping the mouth busy may stop the psychological need to smoke. A simple breathing exercise can also help: take a deep breath through the nose and blow out slowly through the mouth, repeating 10 times.",
      "To manage anger, frustration, irritability, and anxiety during withdrawal, remind yourself that these feelings are temporary and engage in an enjoyable physical activity such as taking a walk. Reduce caffeine by limiting or avoiding coffee, soda, and tea. Try relaxation techniques such as meditation, getting a massage, soaking in a hot bath, or setting aside quiet time alone every morning and evening.",
      "It is common to feel sad for a period of time soon after quitting smoking or using other tobacco products. People with a history of depression often have more severe withdrawal symptoms, and some studies have found that many people with a history of major depression will have a new major depressive episode after quitting. Helpful strategies include getting together with a friend, identifying specific feelings such as tiredness, loneliness, boredom, or hunger and addressing those needs, doing enjoyable physical activities, and asking a doctor about prescription medications that may help with depression.",
      "People who quit may gain weight due to increased appetite, though the weight gain is usually less than 10 pounds, and the health benefits of quitting far outweigh the risks of a small amount of extra weight. To manage this, balance physical activity with calorie intake and consider consulting a nutritionist or diet counselor. Bupropion and certain nicotine replacement products such as nicotine gum and lozenges can help counteract weight gain.",
      "Common triggers for tobacco use fall into three categories. Social triggers include being around others who use tobacco or attending a social gathering. Emotional triggers include feeling stressed, anxious, bored, lonely, sad, frustrated, or upset after an argument, or feeling happy, excited, or relieved. Pattern or activity triggers include starting the day, being in a car, drinking coffee or tea, and enjoying a meal or an alcoholic beverage.",
      "Situational strategies can help avoid relapse around known triggers. Around smokers, limit contact, do not hold cigarettes for others, and excuse yourself when others light up. For morning routines, plan a different wake-up routine and keep healthy substitutes where cigarettes used to be. Many people find it helpful to drink less alcohol or avoid it completely, and to remove ashtrays, lighters, and cigarettes from the car while keeping healthy substitutes on hand.",
      "Nicotine replacement therapy comes in five FDA-approved forms that deliver measured doses of nicotine to relieve cravings and withdrawal symptoms, increasing the likelihood of quitting successfully. The patch, gum, and lozenge are available over the counter, while the nasal spray and inhaler require a prescription. Getting nicotine from a replacement product is far less harmful than from cigarettes, and long-term use has not been associated with serious harmful effects, though these products are not recommended for people who are pregnant or trying to become pregnant. Using a long-acting form like the patch alongside a short-acting form like the gum or lozenge can be especially helpful, and effectiveness improves when combined with advice or counseling from a health care provider.",
      "Two non-nicotine prescription medications are approved to help with quitting. Varenicline (Chantix), approved by FDA in 2006, may ease nicotine cravings and block the pleasurable effects of nicotine if a person resumes smoking. Bupropion (Zyban), a prescription antidepressant approved in 1997, can reduce withdrawal symptoms and the urge to smoke, can be used safely with nicotine replacement products, and along with nortriptyline can help people with a past history of depression who try to quit. Both medications have several associated side effects, so a person should discuss with their doctor whether the medicine is right for them.",
      "Some people claim that alternative approaches such as hypnosis, acupuncture, acupressure, laser therapy, or electrostimulation may help reduce nicotine withdrawal symptoms, but in clinical studies these therapies have not been found to help people quit, and there is no evidence they help tobacco users who are trying to quit. The evidence is also inconclusive about whether e-cigarettes help with smoking cessation, and FDA has not approved any e-cigarette as a cessation therapy. People who smoke are advised to use evidence-based quit strategies, including FDA-approved cessation medication and smoking cessation counseling.",
      "Free help is available for quitting tobacco. Smokefree.gov, created by NCI's Tobacco Control Research Branch, offers personalized quit plans and trigger management information. The NCI Smoking Quitline at 1-877-44U-QUIT (1-877-448-7848) provides individualized counseling, printed information, and referrals to other sources."
