      "Tobacco kills up to half of its users who do not quit. Each year tobacco use causes more than 7 million deaths, a toll that includes an estimated 1.6 million non-smokers who die from exposure to second-hand smoke. There is no safe level of exposure, and all forms of tobacco are harmful.",
      "Around 80% of the world's 1.3 billion tobacco users live in low- and middle-income countries, where the burden of tobacco-related illness and death is heaviest. This concentration reflects where the human and economic costs of tobacco fall most severely.",
      "Cigarettes are the most common form of tobacco consumed worldwide, but they are far from the only one. Other products include waterpipes, cigars, heated tobacco products, bidis, kreteks, and smokeless tobacco. Because all of these forms are harmful, switching between them does not make tobacco use safe.",
      "Second-hand smoke is the smoke that fills enclosed spaces when people burn tobacco products. Exposure causes serious cardiovascular and respiratory diseases, including coronary heart disease and lung cancer, and is responsible for around 1.6 million premature deaths every year. Protecting non-smokers from this smoke is a core part of reducing tobacco harm.",
      "Comprehensive smoke-free laws protect people from second-hand smoke in workplaces and public spaces. As of the data reported, more than one-third of the global population across 79 countries is covered by such laws. These protections benefit both smokers and the non-smokers around them.",
      "Counselling and medication can more than double a tobacco user's chance of quitting successfully. Combining behavioral support with treatment is therefore far more effective than trying to quit with neither. This makes access to structured cessation help a key lever for anyone trying to stop.",
      "Despite the proven benefit of cessation support, national comprehensive cessation services with full or partial cost-coverage are available in only 31 countries. This gap means many tobacco users who want to quit lack affordable access to the counselling and treatment that would improve their odds.",
      "WHO adopted the Framework Convention on Tobacco Control (FCTC) in 2003 as the first international public health treaty, and it now has 183 Party countries. The treaty provides the foundation for coordinated global action to reduce tobacco use and protect populations from its harms.",
      "To help countries put the treaty into practice, WHO introduced the MPOWER package of measures in 2007. The six MPOWER measures are: Monitor tobacco use and prevention policies, Protect people from tobacco smoke, Offer help to quit, Warn about the dangers of tobacco, Enforce bans on advertising and promotion, and Raise taxes on tobacco. Together these measures support both prevention and successful quitting."
