      "Nicotine replacement therapy (NRT) helps people who want to quit smoking by managing the withdrawal symptoms and cravings that make quitting hard. Using NRT increases the chances of successfully quitting by roughly 50 to 70 percent compared with quitting without it.",
      "Nicotine withdrawal commonly causes restlessness, increased appetite, low mood or depression, irritability, and intense cravings. These cravings typically peak about two to three days after a person stops smoking, then gradually ease over the following weeks.",
      "NRT works by delivering nicotine that binds to nicotinic-cholinergic receptors in the brain, which triggers dopamine release in reward-related areas such as the frontal cortex, mesolimbic region, and corpus striatum. This produces the pleasurable and stimulating sensations that smokers normally get from cigarettes, but without the smoke. By substituting a controlled source of nicotine, NRT blunts withdrawal while the person works on breaking the smoking habit.",
      "NRT comes in several forms suited to different needs and preferences. Long-acting transdermal patches provide a steady background level of nicotine throughout the day, while short-acting forms such as gum, lozenges, inhalers, and nasal spray act quickly to relieve sudden cravings. Many people combine a patch with a short-acting form for better craving control.",
      "Short-acting NRT forms work best when used correctly. Nicotine gum should be chewed slowly and then parked against the cheek rather than chewed continuously, and lozenges should be allowed to dissolve slowly over 20 to 30 minutes instead of being swallowed or bitten. Acidic drinks like coffee or soda can reduce absorption, so it helps to avoid them shortly before and during use.",
      "Common side effects of NRT depend on the form used. Patches can cause skin irritation at the application site and vivid dreams, while gum and lozenges may cause mouth or throat irritation, hiccups, or oral ulcers. Other possible effects include nausea, headache, and palpitations, and NRT should be used cautiously by people with cardiovascular disease, with discontinuation if palpitations develop.",
      "Certain groups need extra caution with NRT. For pregnant individuals, comprehensive behavioral support is the preferred first approach, and NRT is considered only when counseling alone is not enough, since nicotine carries theoretical risks to the fetus even though NRT avoids the carbon monoxide and other toxins in cigarette smoke. NRT safety has not been established for people under 18, and older adults or those with liver, kidney, or heart impairment may need lower doses.",
      "Combining medications can improve quit success for some people. Bupropion, an antidepressant, paired with a nicotine patch can enhance results, and varenicline may be combined with NRT under clinical guidance, though this raises the chance of nausea and skin reactions. Extended treatment lasting longer than 12 weeks is sometimes recommended over standard shorter courses when NRT is combined with other cessation medications.",
      "Successful cessation works best as a team effort with ongoing support rather than medication alone. Regular follow-up visits help check on side effects, confirm the person is using NRT correctly, and provide behavioral encouragement. Interprofessional care involving clinicians, nurses, pharmacists, and mental health support, such as structured programs like the Ottawa Model for Smoking Cessation, is associated with higher quit rates.",
      "Nicotine overdose is possible if too much NRT is used, especially alongside continued smoking. Warning signs include nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, dizziness, rapid heartbeat, weakness, and difficulty breathing, and these warrant prompt medical attention. Following the recommended dosing and not smoking while using NRT helps avoid toxicity."
