      "The first cigarette of the day tends to feel the most rewarding because the overnight break from smoking lets desensitized nicotinic receptors recover and become active again. As the number of active receptor sites increases overnight and into the early morning, withdrawal symptoms and craving intensify, which is why the morning urge to smoke is often strongest.",
      "Brain imaging with PET scans shows that tobacco use produces a marked reduction in the activity of monoamine oxidase (MAO), the enzyme that normally breaks down dopamine. Lowering both forms of this enzyme, MAO-A and MAO-B, results in higher dopamine levels, adding to nicotine's reinforcing effect beyond its direct action on nicotinic receptors.",
      "Nicotine also acts on other neurotransmitter systems involved in mood and reward. Nicotinic agonists trigger a calcium-dependent release of GABA in parts of the brain, and ongoing daily nicotine exposure lowers serotonin (5-HT) activity in the hippocampus, changes that contribute to the mood disturbances felt during withdrawal.",
