      "This qualitative study explored why adolescents want to quit vaping, what barriers they face, and which cessation strategies they recommend. Researchers conducted semi-structured interviews with 11 high school students who had vaped nicotine in the past 90 days. The goal was to ground vaping-cessation support in the lived experience of teens who vape.",
      "Teens cited several reasons for wanting to quit vaping. These included the financial cost of devices and pods, health worries such as lung damage, reduced lung capacity, asthma, and cough, and the toll on mood and focus including irritability, depressive mood swings, worsening anxiety, and distraction from schoolwork. Many also described being addicted, experiencing strong cravings and feeling desperate when they could not vape.",
      "Adolescents described 'nic-sick' symptoms tied to nicotine, including nausea, headaches, and vomiting from withdrawal or from taking in too much nicotine. These physical effects were a recurring motivator to cut back or quit. The discomfort made vaping feel less appealing over time.",
